snippet.title: Amber Heard arrives at UK High Court
snippet.description:
(7 Jul 2020) AMBER HEARD ARRIVES AT UK HIGH COURT 
Amber Heard arrived at Britain's High Court on Tuesday (7 JULY 2020) to attend a hearing of ex-husband Johnny Depp's claim against The Sun’s publisher, News Group Newspapers, over a story alleging he was abusive to her.
The actor is suing the publication, along with its executive editor, Dan Wootton, for libel over an article that branded him a “wife beater.” 
The paper ran a story in 2018 claiming Depp was violent towards Heard.
Depp strongly denies the allegations.
Depp, 57, and model-actress Heard, 34, have accused each other of acting abusively.

snippet.title: Johnny Depp and Amber Heard arrive at High Court for three-week libel showdown
snippet.description:
Lawyers for the former couple have been working to make sure they arrive at London's High Court at separate times for the showdown to ensure there is no risk of them bumping into one another outside. Depp is suing The Sun newspaper and its executive editor Dan Wootton over allegations the actor behaved like a 'violent monster' towards his former wife during their troubled two-year marriage.

snippet.title: Amber Heard arrives at court for the last day of libel case
snippet.description:
(28 Jul 2020) AMBER HEARD ARRIVES AT COURT FOR THE LAST DAY OF LIBEL CASE
Johnny Depp’s libel case against a British tabloid that accused him of abusing ex-wife Amber Heard wraps up Tuesday after three weeks of court hearings that dissected a toxic celebrity love affair.
  
The “Pirates of the Caribbean” star is suing News Group Newspapers, publisher of The Sun, and the newspaper’s executive editor, Dan Wootton, at the High Court in London over an April 2018 article that called him a “wife-beater.” He strongly denies being violent to Heard and says her claims are a “hoax.”
  
Depp’s lawyer, David Sherborne, is due to make his closing arguments that will last most of the day. Then judge Andrew Nicol will retire to sift claim and counterclaim as he considers his verdict. He is expected to hand down his ruling in several weeks.
